When the food (response) is ready, Nginx delivers it back to the customer.

ğŸ”„ So Nginx is not an API server, but it sits in front of your API, doing jobs like:
Accepting requests (like an entry gate)

Passing them to your API server (e.g., a Node.js or Django backend)

Returning the response to the user

Handling SSL (HTTPS)

Caching things if needed

Blocking bad requests (basic security)

ğŸ”§ Example:
Without Nginx:
User â†’ http://api.example.com â†’ Node.js API handles everything

With Nginx:
User â†’ http://api.example.com â†’ Nginx â†’ Node.js API

Nginx listens on port 80 or 443 (web ports) and forwards the request to your actual backend API (maybe on port 3000 or 5000).

ğŸ§¾ Summary:
Term	Is it the API?	What it does
Nginx	âŒ No	Forwards requests to your API, acts like a gatekeeper
API Server (e.g., Node.js)	âœ… Yes	Contains your actual logic and data processing
So, Nginx listens to requests but doesn't have the API logic itself â€“ it just helps the API work better and more securely.

